# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ocean-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] For years, displacement mapping was a peculiarity of high-end rendering systems like PhotoRealistic RenderMan, while realtime APIs, like OpenGL and DirectX, were only starting to use this feature.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] One of the reasons for this is that the original implementation of displacement mapping required an adaptive tessellation of the surface in order to obtain enough micropolygons whose size matched the size of a pixel on the screen.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Displacement mapping includes the term mapping which refers to a texture map being used to modulate the displacement strength.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The displacement direction is usually the local surface normal.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Today, many renderers allow programmable shading which can create high quality (multidimensional) procedural textures and patterns at arbitrarily high frequencies.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The use of the term mapping becomes arguable then, as no texture map is involved anymore.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Therefore, the broader term **displacement** is often used today to refer to a super concept that also includes displacement based on a texture map.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Renderers using the REYES algorithm, or similar approaches based on micropolygons, have allowed displacement mapping at arbitrary high frequencies since they became available almost 20 years ago.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The first commercially available renderer to implement a micropolygon displacement mapping approach through REYES was Pixar's PhotoRealistic RenderMan.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Micropolygon renderers commonly tessellate geometry themselves at a granularity suitable for the image being rendered.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] That is: the modeling application delivers high-level primitives to the renderer.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Examples include true NURBS- or subdivision surfaces.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The renderer then tessellates this geometry into micropolygons at render time using view-based constraints derived from the image being rendered.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Other renderers that require the modeling application to deliver objects pre-tessellated into arbitrary polygons or even triangles have defined the term displacement mapping as moving the vertices of these polygons.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Often the displacement direction is also limited to the surface normal at the vertex.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] While conceptually similar, those polygons are usually a lot larger than micropolygons.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The quality achieved from this approach is thus limited by the geometry's tessellation density a long time before the renderer gets access to it.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] This difference between displacement mapping in micropolygon renderers vs. displacement mapping in a non-tessellating (macro)polygon renderers can often lead to confusion in conversations between people whose exposure to each technology or implementation is limited.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Even more so, as in recent years, many non-micropolygon renderers have added the ability to do displacement mapping of a quality similar to that which a micropolygon renderer is able to deliver naturally.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] To distinguish between the crude pre-tessellation-based displacement these renderers did before, the term **sub-pixel displacement** was introduced to describe this feature.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Sub-pixel displacement commonly refers to finer re-tessellation of geometry that was already tessellated into polygons.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] This re-tessellation results in micropolygons or often microtriangles.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] The vertices of these then get moved along their normals to achieve the displacement mapping.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] True micropolygon renderers have always been able to do what sub-pixel-displacement achieved only recently, but at a higher quality and in arbitrary displacement directions.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Recent developments seem to indicate that some of the renderers that use sub-pixel displacement move towards supporting higher level geometry too.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] As the vendors of these renderers are likely to keep using the term sub-pixel displacement, this will probably lead to more obfuscation of what displacement mapping really stands for, in 3D computer graphics.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] In reference to Microsoft's proprietary High Level Shader Language, displacement mapping can be interpreted as a kind of "vertex-texture mapping" where the values of the texture map do not alter pixel colors (as is much more common), but instead change the position of vertices.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] Unlike bump, normal and parallax mapping, all of which can be said to "fake" the behavior of displacement mapping, in this way a genuinely *rough* surface can be produced from a texture.
[src:ocean-rendering/displacement-mapping] It has to be used in conjunction with adaptive tessellation techniques (that increases the number of rendered polygons according to current viewing settings) to produce highly detailed meshes.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A **fast Fourier transform** (**FFT**) is an algorithm that computes the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), or its inverse (IDFT), of a sequence.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A Fourier transform converts a signal from its original domain (often time or space) to a representation in the frequency domain and vice versa.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The DFT is obtained by decomposing a sequence of values into components of different frequencies.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This operation is useful in many fields, but computing it directly from the definition is often too slow to be practical.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT rapidly computes such transformations by factorizing the DFT matrix into a product of sparse (mostly zero) factors.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] As a result, it manages to reduce the complexity of computing the DFT from ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ , which arises if one simply applies the definition of DFT, to ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ , where n is the length of the sequence.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The difference in speed can be enormous, especially for long sequences where n may be in the thousands or millions.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] As the FFT is merely an algebraic refactoring of terms within the DFT, the DFT and the FFT both perform mathematically equivalent and interchangeable operations, assuming that all terms are computed with infinite precision.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] However, in the presence of round-off error, many FFT algorithms are much more accurate than evaluating the DFT definition directly or indirectly.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] There are many different FFT algorithms based on a wide range of published theories, from simple complex-number arithmetic to group theory and number theory.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The best-known FFT algorithms depend upon the factorization of n, but there are FFTs with $O(n\log n)$ complexity for all n, including prime values.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Many FFT algorithms depend only on the fact that ${\textstyle e^{-2\pi i/n}}$ is an nth primitive root of unity, and thus can be applied to analogous transforms over any finite field, such as number-theoretic transforms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Since the inverse DFT is the same as the DFT, but with the opposite sign in the exponent and a 1/*n* factor, any FFT algorithm can easily be adapted for it.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Fast Fourier transforms are widely used for applications in engineering, music, science, and mathematics.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The basic ideas were popularized in 1965, but some algorithms had been derived as early as 1805.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In 1994, Gilbert Strang described the FFT as "the most important numerical algorithm of our lifetime", and it was included in Top 10 Algorithms of 20th Century by the IEEE magazine *Computing in Science & Engineering*.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The development of fast algorithms for DFT was prefigured in Carl Friedrich Gauss's unpublished 1805 work on the orbits of asteroids Pallas and Juno.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Gauss wanted to interpolate the orbits from sample observations; his method was very similar to the one that would be published in 1965 by James Cooley and John Tukey, who are generally credited for the invention of the modern generic FFT algorithm.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] While Gauss's work predated even Joseph Fourier's 1822 results, he did not analyze the method's complexity, and eventually used other methods to achieve the same end.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Between 1805 and 1965, some versions of FFT were published by other authors.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Frank Yates in 1932 published his version called *interaction algorithm*, which provided efficient computation of Hadamard and Walsh transforms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Yates' algorithm is still used in the field of statistical design and analysis of experiments.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Danielson and Cornelius Lanczos published their version to compute DFT for x-ray crystallography, a field where calculation of Fourier transforms presented a formidable bottleneck.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Good published a paper establishing the prime-factor FFT algorithm that applies to discrete Fourier transforms of size ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ , where $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are coprime.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] James Cooley and John Tukey independently rediscovered these earlier algorithms and published a more general FFT in 1965 that is applicable when n is composite and not necessarily a power of 2, as well as analyzing the ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ scaling.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Tukey came up with the idea during a meeting of President Kennedy's Science Advisory Committee, where a discussion topic involved detecting nuclear tests by the Soviet Union by setting up sensors to surround the country from outside.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] To analyze the output of these sensors, an FFT algorithm would be needed.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In discussion with Tukey, Richard Garwin recognized the general applicability of the algorithm not just to national security problems, but also to a wide range of problems including one of immediate interest to him, determining the periodicities of the spin orientations in a 3-D crystal of Helium-3.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Garwin gave Tukey's idea to Cooley (both worked at IBM's Watson labs) for implementation.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Cooley and Tukey published the paper in a relatively short time of six months.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] As Tukey did not work at IBM, the patentability of the idea was doubted and the algorithm went into the public domain, which, through the computing revolution of the next decade, made FFT one of the indispensable algorithms in digital signal processing.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] where $e^{i2\pi /n}$ is a primitive nth root of 1.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating this definition directly requires ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ operations: there are n outputs Xk , and each output requires a sum of n terms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT is any method to compute the same results in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] All known FFT algorithms require ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations, although there is no known proof that lower complexity is impossible.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] To illustrate the savings of an FFT, consider the count of complex multiplications and additions for ${\textstyle n=4096}$ data points.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating the DFT's sums directly involves ${\textstyle n^{2}}$ complex multiplications and ${\textstyle n(n-1)}$ complex additions, of which ${\textstyle O(n)}$ operations can be saved by eliminating trivial operations such as multiplications by 1, leaving about 30 million operations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] By far the most commonly used FFT is the Cooley–Tukey algorithm.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The best known use of the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is to divide the transform into two pieces of size *n*/2 at each step, and is therefore limited to power-of-two sizes, but any factorization can be used in general (as was known to both Gauss and Cooley/Tukey).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] These are called the *radix-2* and *mixed-radix* cases, respectively (and other variants such as the split-radix FFT have their own names as well).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Although the basic idea is recursive, most traditional implementations rearrange the algorithm to avoid explicit recursion.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Also, because the Cooley–Tukey algorithm breaks the DFT into smaller DFTs, it can be combined arbitrarily with any other algorithm for the DFT, such as those described below.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] For ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ with coprime ${\textstyle n_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle n_{2}}$ , one can use the prime-factor (Good–Thomas) algorithm (PFA), based on the Chinese remainder theorem, to factorize the DFT similarly to Cooley–Tukey but without the twiddle factors.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Algorithms that recursively factorize the DFT into smaller operations other than DFTs include the Bruun and QFT algorithms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] (The Rader–Brenner and QFT algorithms were proposed for power-of-two sizes, but it is possible that they could be adapted to general composite n.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm applies to arbitrary even composite sizes.) Bruun's algorithm, in particular, is based on interpreting the FFT as a recursive factorization of the polynomial $z^{n}-1$ , here into real-coefficient polynomials of the form $z^{m}-1$ and $z^{2m}+az^{m}+1$ .
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, Winograd also makes use of the PFA as well as an algorithm by Rader for FFTs of *prime* sizes.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Hexagonal fast Fourier transform (HFFT) aims at computing an efficient FFT for the hexagonally-sampled data by using a new addressing scheme for hexagonal grids, called Array Set Addressing (ASA).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] and efficient FFT algorithms have been designed for this situation (see e.g., Sorensen, 1987).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] One approach consists of taking an ordinary algorithm (e.g., Cooley–Tukey) and removing the redundant parts of the computation, saving roughly a factor of two in time and memory.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Alternatively, it is possible to express an *even*-length real-input DFT as a complex DFT of half the length (whose real and imaginary parts are the even/odd elements of the original real data), followed by $O(n)$ post-processing operations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm (above) is another method that was initially proposed to take advantage of real inputs, but it has not proved popular.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] There are further FFT specializations for the cases of real data that have even/odd symmetry, in which case one can gain another factor of roughly two in time and memory and the DFT becomes the discrete cosine/sine transform(s) (DCT/DST).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Instead of directly modifying an FFT algorithm for these cases, DCTs/DSTs can also be computed via FFTs of real data combined with $O(n)$ pre- and post-processing.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] What is the lower bound on the complexity of fast Fourier transform algorithms?
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A fundamental question of longstanding theoretical interest is to prove lower bounds on the complexity and exact operation counts of fast Fourier transforms, and many open problems remain.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] It is not rigorously proved whether DFTs truly require ${\textstyle \Omega (n\log n)}$ (i.e., order *$n\log n$* or greater) operations, even for the simple case of power of two sizes, although no algorithms with lower complexity are known.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, the count of arithmetic operations is usually the focus of such questions, although actual performance on modern-day computers is determined by many other factors such as cache or CPU pipeline optimization.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Following work by Shmuel Winograd (1978), a tight $\Theta (n)$ lower bound is known for the number of real multiplications required by an FFT.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] It can be shown that only ${\textstyle 4n-2\log _{2}^{2}(n)-2\log _{2}(n)-4}$ irrational real multiplications are required to compute a DFT of power-of-two length $n=2^{m}$ .
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Moreover, explicit algorithms that achieve this count are known (Heideman & Burrus, 1986; Duhamel, 1990).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] However, these algorithms require too many additions to be practical, at least on modern computers with hardware multipliers (Duhamel, 1990; Frigo & Johnson, 2005).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A tight lower bound is not known on the number of required additions, although lower bounds have been proved under some restrictive assumptions on the algorithms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In 1973, Morgenstern proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound on the addition count for algorithms where the multiplicative constants have bounded magnitudes (which is true for most but not all FFT algorithms).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Pan (1986) proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound assuming a bound on a measure of the FFT algorithm's *asynchronicity*, but the generality of this assumption is unclear.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A third problem is to minimize the *total* number of real multiplications and additions, sometimes called the *arithmetic complexity* (although in this context it is the exact count and not the asymptotic complexity that is being considered).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Again, no tight lower bound has been proven.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Since 1968, however, the lowest published count for power-of-two n was long achieved by the split-radix FFT algorithm, which requires ${\textstyle 4n\log _{2}(n)-6n+8}$ real multiplications and additions for *n* > 1.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This was further reduced to ${\textstyle \sim {\frac {34}{9}}n\log _{2}n}$ (Johnson and Frigo, 2007; Lundy and Van Buskirk, 2007).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Most of the attempts to lower or prove the complexity of FFT algorithms have focused on the ordinary complex-data case, because it is the simplest.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] However, complex-data FFTs are so closely related to algorithms for related problems, such as real-data FFTs, discrete cosine transforms, discrete Hartley transforms, and so on, that any improvement in one of these would immediately lead to improvements in the others (Duhamel & Vetterli, 1990).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] All of the FFT algorithms discussed above compute the DFT exactly (i.e., neglecting floating-point errors).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A few FFT algorithms have been proposed, however, that compute the DFT *approximately*, with an error that can be made arbitrarily small at the expense of increased computations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms trade the approximation error for increased speed or other properties.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] For example, an approximate FFT algorithm by Edelman et al.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] (1999) achieves lower communication requirements for parallel computing with the help of a fast multipole method.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A wavelet-based approximate FFT by Guo and Burrus (1996) takes sparse inputs/outputs (time/frequency localization) into account more efficiently than is possible with an exact FFT.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Another algorithm for approximate computation of a subset of the DFT outputs is due to Shentov et al.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The Edelman algorithm works equally well for sparse and non-sparse data, since it is based on the compressibility (rank deficiency) of the Fourier matrix itself rather than the compressibility (sparsity) of the data.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] FFT algorithms have errors when finite-precision floating-point arithmetic is used, but these errors are typically quite small; most FFT algorithms, e.g., Cooley–Tukey, have excellent numerical properties as a consequence of the pairwise summation structure of the algorithms.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The upper bound on the relative error for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon \log n)}$ , compared to ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon n^{3/2})}$ for the naïve DFT formula, where 𝜀 is the machine floating-point relative precision.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In fact, the root mean square (rms) errors are much better than these upper bounds, being only ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {\log n}})}$ for Cooley–Tukey and ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {n}})}$ for the naïve DFT (Schatzman, 1996).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] These results, however, are very sensitive to the accuracy of the twiddle factors used in the FFT (i.e. the trigonometric function values), and it is not unusual for incautious FFT implementations to have much worse accuracy, e.g. if they use inaccurate trigonometric recurrence formulas.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Some FFTs other than Cooley–Tukey, such as the Rader–Brenner algorithm, are intrinsically less stable.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In fixed-point arithmetic, the finite-precision errors accumulated by FFT algorithms are worse, with rms errors growing as ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {n}})}$ for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm (Welch, 1969).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Achieving this accuracy requires careful attention to scaling to minimize loss of precision, and fixed-point FFT algorithms involve rescaling at each intermediate stage of decompositions like Cooley–Tukey.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] To verify the correctness of an FFT implementation, rigorous guarantees can be obtained in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ time by a simple procedure checking the linearity, impulse-response, and time-shift properties of the transform on random inputs (Ergün, 1995).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The values for intermediate frequencies may be obtained by various averaging methods.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Equivalently, it is the composition of a sequence of *d* sets of one-dimensional DFTs, performed along one dimension at a time (in any order).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This compositional viewpoint immediately provides the simplest and most common multidimensional DFT algorithm, known as the **row-column** algorithm (after the two-dimensional case, below).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] That is, one simply performs a sequence of d one-dimensional FFTs (by any of the above algorithms): first you transform along the *n*1 dimension, then along the *n*2 dimension, and so on (actually, any ordering works).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This method is easily shown to have the usual ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity, where ${\textstyle n=n_{1}\cdot n_{2}\cdots n_{d}}$ is the total number of data points transformed.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In more than two dimensions, it is often advantageous for cache locality to group the dimensions recursively.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] For example, a three-dimensional FFT might first perform two-dimensional FFTs of each planar slice for each fixed *n*1, and then perform the one-dimensional FFTs along the *n*1 direction.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Still, this remains a straightforward variation of the row-column algorithm that ultimately requires only a one-dimensional FFT algorithm as the base case, and still has $O(n\log n)$ complexity.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Yet another variation is to perform matrix transpositions in between transforming subsequent dimensions, so that the transforms operate on contiguous data; this is especially important for out-of-core and distributed memory situations where accessing non-contiguous data is extremely time-consuming.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] There are other multidimensional FFT algorithms that are distinct from the row-column algorithm, although all of them have ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Perhaps the simplest non-row-column FFT is the vector-radix FFT algorithm, which is a generalization of the ordinary Cooley–Tukey algorithm where one divides the transform dimensions by a vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{d}\right)}$ of radices at each step.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] (This may also have cache benefits.) The simplest case of vector-radix is where all of the radices are equal (e.g., vector-radix-2 divides *all* of the dimensions by two), but this is not necessary.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Vector radix with only a single non-unit radix at a time, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(1,\ldots ,1,r,1,\ldots ,1\right)}$ , is essentially a row-column algorithm.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Other, more complicated, methods include polynomial transform algorithms due to Nussbaumer (1977), which view the transform in terms of convolutions and polynomial products.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] See Duhamel and Vetterli (1990) for more information and references.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A spherical-harmonic algorithm with ${\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}$ complexity is described by Rokhlin and Tygert.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The fast folding algorithm is analogous to the FFT, except that it operates on a series of binned waveforms rather than a series of real or complex scalar values.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Rotation (which in the FFT is multiplication by a complex phasor) is a circular shift of the component waveform .
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Various groups have also published FFT algorithms for non-equispaced data, as reviewed in Potts *et al.* (2001).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms do not strictly compute the DFT (which is only defined for equispaced data), but rather some approximation thereof (a non-uniform discrete Fourier transform, or NDFT, which itself is often computed only approximately).
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] More generally, there are various other methods of spectral estimation.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT is used in digital recording, sampling, additive synthesis and pitch correction software.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT's importance derives from the fact that it has made working in the frequency domain equally computationally feasible as working in the temporal or spatial domain.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] In modern wireless communication standards, the FFT is a critical component for processing signals.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Specifically, it is utilized in Orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) systems, such as 4G LTE and 5G NR.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The efficiency of the FFT allows for high-speed data transmission by dividing a wideband signal into multiple closely spaced orthogonal subcarriers.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This technology is essential for reducing interference and optimizing power consumption in mobile devices.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT can be a poor choice for analyzing signals with non-stationary frequency content—where the frequency characteristics change over time.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] DFTs provide a global frequency estimate, assuming that all frequency components are present throughout the entire signal, which makes it challenging to detect short-lived or transient features within signals.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] For cases where frequency information appears briefly in the signal or generally varies over time, alternatives like the short-time Fourier transform, discrete wavelet transforms, or discrete Hilbert transform can be more suitable.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] These transforms allow for localized frequency analysis by capturing both frequency and time-based information.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] With the explosion of big data in fields such as astronomy, the need for 512K FFTs has arisen for certain interferometry calculations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] require FFTs of tens of billions of points.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] As this size does not fit into main memory, so-called out-of-core FFTs are an active area of research.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] For applications such as MRI, it is necessary to compute DFTs for nonuniformly spaced grid points and/or frequencies.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Multipole-based approaches can compute approximate quantities with factor of runtime increase.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] A function on any compact group, including non-cyclic, has an expansion in terms of a basis of irreducible matrix elements.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] It remains an active area of research to find an efficient algorithm for performing this change of basis.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] on a quantum computer has a subroutine to compute DFT of a binary vector.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] This is implemented as a sequence of 1- or 2-bit quantum gates now known as quantum FFT, which is effectively the Cooley–Tukey FFT realized as a particular factorization of the Fourier matrix.
[src:ocean-rendering/fast-fourier-transform] Extensions to these ideas are currently being explored.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Fluid animation differs from computational fluid dynamics (CFD) in that fluid animation is used primarily for visual effects, whereas computational fluid dynamics is used to study the behavior of fluids in a scientifically rigorous way.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] The development of fluid animation techniques based on the Navier–Stokes equations began in 1996, when Nick Foster and Dimitris Metaxas implemented solutions to 3D Navier-Stokes equations in a computer graphics context, basing their work on a scientific CFD paper by Harlow and Welch from 1965.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Up to that point, a variety of simpler methods had primarily been used, including ad-hoc particle systems, lower dimensional techniques such as height fields, and semi-random turbulent noise fields.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] In 1999, Jos Stam published the "Stable Fluids" method, which exploited a semi-Lagrangian advection technique and implicit integration of viscosity to provide unconditionally stable behaviour.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] This allowed for much larger time steps and therefore faster simulations.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] This general technique was extended by Ronald Fedkiw and co-authors to handle more realistic smoke and fire, as well as complex 3D water simulations using variants of the level-set method.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Some notable academic researchers in this area include Jerry Tessendorf, James F.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] O'Brien, Ron Fedkiw, Mark Carlson, Greg Turk, Robert Bridson, Ken Museth, and Jos Stam.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Many 3D computer graphics programs implement fluid animation techniques.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] RealFlow is a standalone commercial package that has been used to produce visual effects in movies, television shows, commercials, and games.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] RealFlow implements a fluid-implicit particle (FLIP; an extension of the Particle-in-cell method) solver, a hybrid grid, and a particle method that allows for advanced features such as foam and spray.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Maya and Houdini are two other commercial 3D computer graphics programs that allow for fluid animation.
[src:ocean-rendering/fluid-animation] Blender is an open-source 3D computer graphics program that utilized a particle-based Lattice Boltzmann method for animating fluids until the integration of the open-source mantaflow project in 2020 with a wide range of Navier-Stokes solver variants.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] In fluid dynamics, a **trochoidal wave** or **Gerstner wave** is an exact solution of the Euler equations for periodic surface gravity waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] It describes a progressive wave of permanent form on the surface of an incompressible fluid of infinite depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The free surface of this wave solution is an inverted (upside-down) trochoid – with sharper crests and flat troughs.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] This wave solution was discovered by Gerstner in 1802, and rediscovered independently by Rankine in 1863.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The flow field associated with the trochoidal wave is not irrotational: it has vorticity.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The vorticity is of such a specific strength and vertical distribution that the trajectories of the fluid parcels are closed circles.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] This is in contrast with the usual experimental observation of Stokes drift associated with the wave motion.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Also the phase speed is independent of the trochoidal wave's amplitude, unlike other nonlinear wave-theories (like those of the Stokes wave and cnoidal wave) and observations.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] For these reasons – as well as for the fact that solutions for finite fluid depth are lacking – trochoidal waves are of limited use for engineering applications.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] In computer graphics, the rendering of realistic-looking ocean waves can be done by use of so-called **Gerstner waves**.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] This is a multi-component and multi-directional extension of the traditional Gerstner wave, often using fast Fourier transforms to make (real-time) animation feasible.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The phase speed satisfies the dispersion relation: $c^{2}={\frac {g}{k}},$ which is independent of the wave nonlinearity (i.e. does not depend on the wave height H ), and this phase speed c the same as for Airy's linear waves in deep water.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The free surface is a line of constant pressure, and is found to correspond with a line $b=b_{s}$ , where $b_{s}$ is a (nonpositive) constant.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] For $b_{s}=0$ the highest waves occur, with a cusp-shaped crest.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Note that the highest (irrotational) Stokes wave has a crest angle of 120°, instead of the 0° for the rotational trochoidal wave.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The vorticity $\varpi$ under the trochoidal wave is: $\varpi (a,b,t)=-{\frac {2kce^{2kb}}{1-e^{2kb}}},$ varying with Lagrangian elevation b and diminishing rapidly with depth below the free surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] A multi-component and multi-directional extension of the Lagrangian description of the free-surface motion – as used in Gerstner's trochoidal wave – is used in computer graphics for the simulation of ocean waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] For the classical Gerstner wave the fluid motion exactly satisfies the nonlinear, incompressible and inviscid flow equations below the free surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] However, the extended Gerstner waves do in general not satisfy these flow equations exactly (although they satisfy them approximately, i.e. for the linearised Lagrangian description by potential flow).
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] This description of the ocean can be programmed very efficiently by use of the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Moreover, the resulting ocean waves from this process look realistic, as a result of the nonlinear deformation of the free surface (due to the Lagrangian specification of the motion): sharper crests and flatter troughs.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The mathematical description of the free-surface in these Gerstner waves can be as follows: the horizontal coordinates are denoted as x and z , and the vertical coordinate is y .
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The latter two, $k_{m}$ and $\omega _{m},$ can not be chosen independently but are related through the dispersion relation: $\omega _{m}^{2}=g\,k_{m}\tanh \left(k_{m}\,h\right),$ with h the mean water depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] The choice of the various parameters $a_{m},k_{x,m},k_{z,m}$ and $\phi _{m}$ for $m=1,\dots ,M,$ and a certain mean depth h determines the form of the ocean surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] A clever choice is needed in order to exploit the possibility of fast computation by means of the FFT.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Tessendorf (2001) for a description how to do this.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Most often, the wavenumbers are chosen on a regular grid in $(k_{x},k_{z})$ -space.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] Thereafter, the amplitudes $a_{m}$ and phases $\phi _{m}$ are chosen randomly in accord with the variance-density spectrum of a certain desired sea state.
[src:ocean-rendering/gerstner-wave] In rendering, also the normal vector ${\boldsymbol {n}}$ to the surface is often needed.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Ocean dynamics has traditionally been investigated by sampling from instruments in situ.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The mixed layer is nearest to the surface and can vary in thickness from 10 to 500 meters.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] This layer has properties such as temperature, salinity and dissolved oxygen which are uniform with depth reflecting a history of active turbulence (the atmosphere has an analogous planetary boundary layer).
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] However, it becomes zero at the base of the mixed layer.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Turbulence again increases below the base of the mixed layer due to shear instabilities.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] At extratropical latitudes this layer is deepest in late winter as a result of surface cooling and winter storms and quite shallow in summer.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Its dynamics is governed by turbulent mixing as well as Ekman transport, exchanges with the overlying atmosphere, and horizontal advection.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The upper ocean, characterized by warm temperatures and active motion, varies in depth from 100 m or less in the tropics and eastern oceans to in excess of 800 meters in the western subtropical oceans.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] This layer exchanges properties such as heat and freshwater with the atmosphere on timescales of a few years.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Below the mixed layer the upper ocean is generally governed by the hydrostatic and geostrophic relationships.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Exceptions include the deep tropics and coastal regions.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The deep ocean is both cold and dark with generally weak velocities (although limited areas of the deep ocean are known to have significant recirculations).
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The deep ocean is supplied with water from the upper ocean in only a few limited geographical regions: the subpolar North Atlantic and several sinking regions around the Antarctic.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Because of the weak supply of water to the deep ocean the average residence time of water in the deep ocean is measured in hundreds of years.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] In this layer as well the hydrostatic and geostrophic relationships are generally valid and mixing is generally quite weak.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Here "u" is zonal velocity, "v" is meridional velocity, "w" is vertical velocity, "p" is pressure, "ρ" is density, "T" is temperature, "S" is salinity, "g" is acceleration due to gravity, "τ" is wind stress, and "f" is the Coriolis parameter.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] "Q" is the heat input to the ocean, while "P-E" is the freshwater input to the ocean.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Mixed layer dynamics are quite complicated; however, in some regions some simplifications are possible.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The wind-driven horizontal transport in the mixed layer is approximately described by Ekman Layer dynamics in which vertical diffusion of momentum balances the Coriolis effect and wind stress.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] This Ekman transport is superimposed on geostrophic flow associated with horizontal gradients of density.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Horizontal convergences and divergences within the mixed layer due, for example, to Ekman transport convergence imposes a requirement that ocean below the mixed layer must move fluid particles vertically.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] But one of the implications of the geostrophic relationship is that the magnitude of horizontal motion must greatly exceed the magnitude of vertical motion.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Thus the weak vertical velocities associated with Ekman transport convergence (measured in meters per day) cause horizontal motion with speeds of 10 centimeters per second or more.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] The mathematical relationship between vertical and horizontal velocities can be derived by expressing the idea of conservation of angular momentum for a fluid on a rotating sphere.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] This relationship (with a couple of additional approximations) is known to oceanographers as the Sverdrup relation.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Among its implications is the result that the horizontal convergence of Ekman transport observed to occur in the subtropical North Atlantic and Pacific forces southward flow throughout the interior of these two oceans.
[src:ocean-rendering/ocean-dynamics] Western boundary currents (the Gulf Stream and Kuroshio) exist in order to return water to higher latitude.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In fluid dynamics, a **wind wave**, or **wind-generated water wave**, is a surface wave that occurs on the free surface of bodies of water as a result of the wind blowing over the water's surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The contact distance in the direction of the wind is known as the *fetch*.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves in the oceans can travel thousands of kilometers before reaching land.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves on Earth range in size from small ripples to waves over 30 m (100 ft) high, being limited by wind speed, duration, fetch, and water depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] When directly generated and affected by local wind, a wind wave system is called a **wind sea**.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves will travel in a great circle route after being generated – curving slightly left in the southern hemisphere and slightly right in the northern hemisphere.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] After moving out of the area of fetch and no longer being affected by the local wind, wind waves are called *swells* and can travel thousands of kilometers.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A noteworthy example of this is waves generated south of Tasmania during heavy winds that will travel across the Pacific to southern California, producing desirable surfing conditions.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves in the ocean are also called **ocean surface waves** and are mainly *gravity waves*, where gravity is the main equilibrium force.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves have a certain amount of randomness: subsequent waves differ in height, duration, and shape with limited predictability.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] They can be described as a stochastic process, in combination with the physics governing their generation, growth, propagation, and decay – as well as governing the interdependence between flow quantities such as the water surface movements, flow velocities, and water pressure.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The key statistics of wind waves (both seas and swells) in evolving sea states can be predicted with wind wave models.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Although waves are usually considered in the water seas of Earth, the hydrocarbon seas of Titan may also have wind-driven waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves in bodies of water may also be generated by other causes, both at the surface and underwater (such as watercraft, animals, waterfalls, landslides, earthquakes, bubbles, and impact events).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The great majority of large breakers seen at a beach result from distant winds.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind duration – the time for which the wind has blown over the water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] All of these factors work together to determine the size of the water waves and the structure of the flow within them.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A fully developed sea has the maximum wave size theoretically possible for a wind of specific strength, duration, and fetch.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Further exposure to that specific wind could only cause a dissipation of energy due to the breaking of wave tops and formation of "whitecaps".
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves in a given area typically have a range of heights.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] For weather reporting and for scientific analysis of wind wave statistics, their characteristic height over a period of time is usually expressed as *significant wave height*.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This figure represents an average height of the highest one-third of the waves in a given time period (usually chosen somewhere in the range from 20 minutes to twelve hours), or in a specific wave or storm system.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The significant wave height is also the value a "trained observer" (e.g. from a ship's crew) would estimate from visual observation of a sea state.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Given the variability of wave height, the largest individual waves are likely to be somewhat less than twice the reported significant wave height for a particular day or storm.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wave formation on an initially flat water surface by wind is started by a random distribution of normal pressure of turbulent wind flow over the water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This pressure fluctuation produces normal and tangential stresses in the surface water, which generates waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] There is a random distribution of normal pressure to the water surface from the turbulent wind.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Correlations between air and water motions are neglected.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The second mechanism involves wind shear forces on the water surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Miles suggested a surface wave generation mechanism that is initiated by turbulent wind shear flows based on the inviscid Orr–Sommerfeld equation in 1957.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] He found the energy transfer from the wind to the water surface is proportional to the curvature of the velocity profile of the wind at the point where the mean wind speed is equal to the wave speed.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Since the wind speed profile is logarithmic to the water surface, the curvature has a negative sign at this point.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This relation shows the wind flow transferring its kinetic energy to the water surface at their interface.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Generally, these wave formation mechanisms occur together on the water surface and eventually produce fully developed waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The winds keep acting on the initially rippled sea surface causing the waves to become larger.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the waves grow, the pressure differences get larger causing the growth rate to increase.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Finally, the shear instability expedites the wave growth exponentially.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Ripples appear on smooth water (i.e. glassy) when the wind blows, but will die quickly if the wind stops.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The restoring force that allows them to propagate is surface tension.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Sea waves are larger-scale, often irregular motions that form under sustained winds.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] These waves tend to last much longer, even after the wind has died, and the restoring force that allows them to propagate is gravity.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As waves propagate away from their area of origin, they naturally separate into groups of common direction and wavelength.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The sets of waves formed in this manner are known as swells.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The Pacific Ocean is 19,800 km (12,300 mi) from Indonesia to the coast of Colombia and, based on an average wavelength of 76.5 m (251 ft), would have ~258,824 swells over that width.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] It is sometimes alleged that out of a set of waves, the seventh wave in a set is always the largest; while this isn't the case, the waves in the middle of a given set tend to be larger than those before and after them.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Individual "rogue waves" (also called "freak waves", "monster waves", "killer waves", or "king waves") much higher than the other waves in the sea state can occur.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In the case of the Draupner wave, its 25 m (82 ft) height was 2.2 times the significant wave height.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Such waves are distinct from tides, caused by the Moon and Sun's gravitational pull, tsunamis that are caused by underwater earthquakes or landslides, and waves generated by underwater explosions or the fall of meteorites—all having far longer wavelengths than wind waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The largest ever recorded wind waves are not rogue waves, but standard waves in extreme sea states.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] For example, 29.1 m (95 ft) high waves were recorded aboard the RRS *Discovery*, in a sea with 18.5 m (61 ft) significant wave height, so the highest wave was only 1.6 times the significant wave height.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The biggest recorded by a buoy (as of 2011) was 32.3 m (106 ft) high during the 2007 typhoon Krosa near Taiwan.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Ocean waves can be classified based on: the disturbing force that creates them; the extent to which the disturbing force continues to influence them after formation; the extent to which the restoring force weakens or flattens them; and their wavelength or period.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Seismic sea waves have a period of about 20 minutes, and speeds of 760 km/h (470 mph).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves (deep-water waves) have a period up to about 20 seconds.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The speed of all ocean waves is controlled by gravity, wavelength, and water depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Most characteristics of ocean waves depend on the relationship between their wavelength and water depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wavelength determines the size of the orbits of water molecules within a wave, but water depth determines the shape of the orbits.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The paths of water molecules in a wind wave are circular only when the wave is traveling in deep water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A wave cannot "feel" the bottom when it moves through water deeper than half its wavelength because too little wave energy is contained in the water movement below that depth.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves moving through water deeper than half their wavelength are known as deep-water waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] On the other hand, the orbits of water molecules in waves moving through shallow water are flattened by the proximity of the sea bottom surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves in water shallower than 1/20 their original wavelength are known as shallow-water waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Transitional waves travel through water deeper than 1/20 their original wavelength but shallower than half their original wavelength.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In general, the longer the wavelength, the faster the wave energy will move through the water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] where C is speed (celerity), L is the wavelength, and T is the period (in seconds).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Thus the speed of the wave derives from the functional dependence $L(T)$ of the wavelength on the period (the dispersion relation).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] where g is the acceleration due to gravity, 9.8 meters (32 feet) per second squared.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] when C is measured in meters per second and L in meters.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In both formulas the wave speed is proportional to the square root of the wavelength.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] where C is speed (in meters per second), g is the acceleration due to gravity, and d is the depth of the water (in meters).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The period of a wave remains unchanged regardless of the depth of water through which it is moving.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As deep-water waves enter the shallows and feel the bottom, however, their speed is reduced, and their crests "bunch up", so their wavelength shortens.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Sea state can be described by the **sea wave spectrum** or just **wave spectrum** $S(\omega ,\Theta )$ .
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] It is composed of a **wave height spectrum** (WHS) $S(\omega )$ and a **wave direction spectrum** (WDS) $f(\Theta )$ .
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Many interesting properties about the sea state can be found from the wave spectra.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] WHS describes the spectral density of wave height variance ("power") versus wave frequency, with dimension $\{S(\omega )\}=\{{\text{length}}^{2}\cdot {\text{time}}\}$ .
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As waves travel from deep to shallow water, their shape changes (wave height increases, speed decreases, and length decreases as wave orbits become asymmetrical).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wave refraction is the process that occurs when waves interact with the sea bed to slow the velocity of propagation as a function of wavelength and period.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the waves slow down in shoaling water, the crests tend to realign at a decreasing angle to the depth contours.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Varying depths along a wave crest cause the crest to travel at different phase speeds, with those parts of the wave in deeper water moving faster than those in shallow water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This process continues while the depth decreases, and reverses if it increases again, but the wave leaving the shoal area may have changed direction considerably.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Rays—lines normal to wave crests between which a fixed amount of energy flux is contained—converge on local shallows and shoals.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Therefore, the wave energy between rays is concentrated as they converge, with a resulting increase in wave height.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Because these effects are related to a spatial variation in the phase speed, and because the phase speed also changes with the ambient current—due to the Doppler shift—the same effects of refraction and altering wave height also occur due to current variations.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In the case of meeting an adverse current the wave *steepens*, i.e. its wave height increases while the wavelength decreases, similar to the shoaling when the water depth decreases.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Some waves undergo a phenomenon called "breaking".
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A breaking wave is one whose base can no longer support its top, causing it to collapse.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A wave breaks when it runs into shallow water, or when two wave systems oppose and combine forces.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] When the slope, or steepness ratio, of a wave, is too great, breaking is inevitable.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Individual waves in deep water break when the wave steepness—the ratio of the wave height *H* to the wavelength *λ*—exceeds about 0.17, so for *H* > 0.17 *λ*.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In shallow water, with the water depth small compared to the wavelength, the individual waves break when their wave height *H* is larger than 0.8 times the water depth *h*, that is *H* > 0.8 *h*.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Waves can also break if the wind grows strong enough to blow the crest off the base of the wave.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In shallow water, the base of the wave is decelerated by drag on the seabed.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As a result, the upper parts will propagate at a higher velocity than the base and the leading face of the crest will become steeper and the trailing face flatter.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This may be exaggerated to the extent that the leading face forms a barrel profile, with the crest falling forward and down as it extends over the air ahead of the wave.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Three main types of breaking waves are identified by surfers or surf lifesavers.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Their varying characteristics make them more or less suitable for surfing and present different dangers.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Plunging, or dumping: these break suddenly and can "dump" swimmers—pushing them to the bottom with great force.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] These are the preferred waves for experienced surfers.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Strong offshore winds and long wave periods can cause dumpers.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] They are often found where there is a sudden rise in the seafloor, such as a reef or sandbar.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Deceleration of the wave base is sufficient to cause upward acceleration and a significant forward velocity excess of the upper part of the crest.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The peak rises and overtakes the forward face, forming a "barrel" or "tube" as it collapses.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Surging: these may never actually break as they approach the water's edge, as the water below them is very deep.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] These waves can knock swimmers over and drag them back into deeper water.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] When the shoreline is near vertical, waves do not break but are reflected.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Most of the energy is retained in the wave as it returns to seaward.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Interference patterns are caused by superposition of the incident and reflected waves, and the superposition may cause localized instability when peaks cross, and these peaks may break due to instability.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves are mechanical waves that propagate along the interface between water and air; the restoring force is provided by gravity, and so they are often referred to as surface gravity waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the wind blows, pressure and friction perturb the equilibrium of the water surface and transfer energy from the air to the water, forming waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The initial formation of waves by the wind is described in the theory of Phillips from 1957, and the subsequent growth of the small waves has been modeled by Miles, also in 1957.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In linear plane waves of one wavelength in deep water, parcels near the surface move not plainly up and down but in circular orbits: forward above and backward below (compared to the wave propagation direction).
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As a result, the surface of the water forms not an exact sine wave, but more a trochoid with the sharper curves upwards—as modeled in trochoidal wave theory.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind waves are thus a combination of transversal and longitudinal waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] When waves propagate in shallow water, (where the depth is less than half the wavelength) the particle trajectories are compressed into ellipses.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In reality, for finite values of the wave amplitude (height), the particle paths do not form closed orbits; rather, after the passage of each crest, particles are displaced slightly from their previous positions, a phenomenon known as Stokes drift.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the depth below the free surface increases, the radius of the circular motion decreases.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] At a depth equal to half the wavelength λ, the orbital movement has decayed to less than 5% of its value at the surface.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In SI units, with $c_{\text{deep}}$ in m/s, $c_{\text{deep}}\approx 1.25{\sqrt {\lambda }}$ , when $\lambda$ is measured in metres.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This expression tells us that waves of different wavelengths travel at different speeds.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The fastest waves in a storm are the ones with the longest wavelength.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As a result, after a storm, the first waves to arrive on the coast are the long-wavelength swells.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] For intermediate and shallow water, the Boussinesq equations are applicable, combining frequency dispersion and nonlinear effects.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] And in very shallow water, the shallow water equations can be used.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] When several wave trains are present, as is always the case in nature, the waves form groups.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] In deep water, the groups travel at a group velocity which is half of the phase speed.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Following a single wave in a group one can see the wave appearing at the back of the group, growing, and finally disappearing at the front of the group.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the water depth d decreases towards the coast, this will have an effect: wave height changes due to wave shoaling and refraction.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] As the wave height increases, the wave may become unstable when the crest of the wave moves faster than the trough.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] This causes *surf*, a breaking of the waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The movement of wind waves can be captured by wave energy devices.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The velocity of propagation of this energy is the group velocity.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Surfers are very interested in the wave forecasts.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] There are many websites that provide predictions of the surf quality for the upcoming days and weeks.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind wave models are driven by more general weather models that predict the winds and pressures over the oceans, seas, and lakes.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Wind wave models are also an important part of examining the impact of shore protection and beach nourishment proposals.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] For many beach areas there is only patchy information about the wave climate, therefore estimating the effect of wind waves is important for managing littoral environments.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] A wind-generated wave can be predicted based on two parameters: wind speed at 10 m above sea level and wind duration, which must blow over long periods of time to be considered fully developed.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The significant wave height and peak frequency can then be predicted for a certain fetch length.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Ocean water waves generate seismic waves that are globally visible on seismographs.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] There are two principal constituents of the ocean wave-generated seismic microseism.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The strongest of these is the secondary microseism which is created by ocean floor pressures generated by interfering ocean waves and has a spectrum that is generally between approximately 6–12 s periods, or at approximately half of the period of the responsible interfering waves.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The theory for microseism generation by standing waves was provided by Michael Longuet-Higgins in 1950 after in 1941 Pierre Bernard suggested this relation with standing waves on the basis of observations.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] The weaker primary microseism, also globally visible, is generated by dynamic seafloor pressures of propagating waves above shallower (less than several hundred meters depth) regions of the global ocean.
[src:ocean-rendering/wind-wave] Microseisms were first reported in about 1900, and seismic records provide long-term proxy measurements of seasonal and climate-related large-scale wave intensity in Earth's oceans including those associated with anthropogenic global warming.
